If I could capture the moon,
I'd dunk its shiny, cratered hull
into the monstrous Pacific,
and then pull it out
and watch the seawater drip off
its melting yellow walls.

Then, I'd ride its airy crescent
like a steed, into the breeze,
and fill my new lungs
with salty sea spray
from sand-laden springs;
and shredded green grass
from juniper knolls;
and freshly-watered asphalt,
ripe with adolescent rain;
and crude, tarry diesel,
exhausted by hot carbon efforts;
and wispy bonfire smoke
from a rusty old pit,
whose Ash turned to ash
two millenia ago.

But first, I'd need an army;
a regiment of eager ghosts,
who'd glide up and down hallways
that were torn down centuries ago,
whose red clay bricks
had crumbled to ash,
like the corpses
that once housed
their wiley spirits.

At dawn, I'd awaken them
with stainless steel pans,
clanging and banging
'til they'd venture to meet me
in a dewy prairie,
the air stinging sweetly
with brisk morning mist.

And then I'd raise
my fist toward the sky,
and, as one, we'd ascend
to great soaring heights,
and look down, fondly,
as the sun shyly crawls
across the bleak meadow,
through the cracked-open curtains
and winter-woven trees,
their skeletons yearning
for spring-born souls
which grow ripe in the summer
and crudely degrade
by autumn's wavering light.

As we climbed, the Earth spun
on its perennial axis,
and its splendid blue aura
slowly shifted into view,
and the meek houses melded
into broad neighborhoods,
the towns into jungles,
and the lakes into puddles,
until, at last,
the continents retreated
into the ocean,
like impenetrable pimples
on a teenager's face.

By nightfall, we'd reach the moon,
only to find it far, far bigger
than we'd ever imagined,
and after a few feeble attempts
to tame its great splendor,
we conceded,
and coalesced in a shallow crater
to gather our thoughts
and recoup our morale.

The airless abyss was cold,
but I was kept warm
by the hovering breaths
of my newfound companions,
who'd risen from their beds
and burned all their days
to abet my damned mission,
unabashed by their failure.

"Did you know?" I began. "That it couldn't be done?"

The ghosts looked at each other
with their sad, empty eye sockets,
somehow distinct
from their usual state;
I couldn't quite describe it,
but I could tell
that they were ashamed,
or perhaps even resentful
of the arduous task
I had thoughtlessly given them.

Nearly a minute had passed.
Not a word.

Perhaps they were stunned
by my harsh, hollow words,
and by the bitter icicles
that hung from my lashes;
I opened my mouth to speak,
but my words had escaped me.

Then, in a magnificent whir
of golden moonbeams
and silver-strewn orbs
and bronze consolations,
beneath dim constellations,
the ghosts coalesced
into one person -- one face,
bearing features so generic
that I could not describe to you
how they differed from Adam
in any seminal way.

For a moment,
I thought that I was looking
at the graceful face of God,
but as the moments carried
my awed contemplation,
the creature's dark features
stepped into the blinding,
unfiltered sunlight.

I saw a streak of barley locks
and a pair of azure shells,
adorning a face of solemn despair
above a corpus of painted blue.

I was looking at myself,
as in a mirror,
and yet, somehow,
I felt detatched
from my ghostly doppelganger,
though I knew
how many miles
and memories we had shared,
except for the few
I'd only recently earned.

"Yes, I knew", said the ghost,
in a voice so much like my own.
"And so did you." 